There are essentially three approaches to include PUIs, which form the basis of the MS-FLUKSS models: (1) PUIs are not treated as a separate plasma component, but the conservation of mass, momentum, and energy for the mixture is preserved; (2) an isotropic distribution function for PUIs is chosen; PUIs are assumed to be co-moving with the SW ions, and the continuity and pressure equations are solved to describe the PUI motion; and (3) fPUI\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$f_{\mathrm{PUI}}$\end{document} is assumed isotropic beyond shocks, at which it is intrinsically non-isotropic, and proper boundary conditions describing the PUI transition across the TS, or other shocks, treated kinetically, are applied.

