				\begin{document}$<0.4$\end{document} au for He (Sokół et al. 2019b). In the downwind direction it can reach out as far as 20 au in the case of H (Rucinski and Bzowski 1995; Sokół et al. 2019b).

The creation mechanism of the secondary ISNs was anticipated theoretically by Baranov et al. (1981), Baranov and Malama (1993). There are three major species of secondary ISNs: H, He, and O. The existence of secondary ISN H in the heliosphere was confirmed by measurements of the backscattered Lyman-α\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$\alpha $\end{document} radiation (Lallement et al. 2005, 2010). However, the secondary ISN H has not been unambiguously resolved from the primary population in in-situ measurements because the velocity distribution of the secondary ISNs is quite wide due to its higher temperature, and it overlaps the distribution of the primary ISNs (Schwadron et al. 2013; Katushkina et al. 2015). Recently, Katushkina et al. (2021b,a) investigated the possible imprints of the secondary ISN H atoms in the full-sky maps of the H fluxes at the Earth’s orbit. They showed that the maps of the H fluxes with energies 1-20 eV for the solar minimum conditions have two specific features: (1) the main peak of the fluxes is split into two blobs, and (2) there are two tails at high ecliptic latitude near the downwind direction. They claim that these features are pronounced due to a signal of the secondary ISN H.

The secondary ISN He was originally believed to be of negligible abundance compared to the primary population (Müller and Zank 2004). It was because the reaction assumed to be responsible for its creation, He++H→He+H+\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$He^{+} + H \rightarrow He + H^{+}$\end{document}, has a very low cross-section (Barnett et al. 1990). However, Bzowski et al. (2012) pointed out that the cross-section of the charge exchange reaction between neutral He atoms and He+ ions (He++He→He+He+)\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$(He^{+} + He \rightarrow He + He^{+})$\end{document} is comparable to the high cross-section of the charge exchange between H atoms and protons, and interpreted excess He fluxes in the ISN He observations by IBEX as a secondary component (see Fig. 13). Because of the relatively high abundance of He+ ions in the VLISM near the heliosphere (Frisch and Slavin 2003), appreciable amounts of the secondary ISN He atoms should be produced in the OHS. Kubiak et al. (2014) found that the He signal observed by the IBEX-Lo instrument on IBEX is explained as a superposition of the unperturbed ISN He gas and an additional flow component of He atoms, which they called the Warm Breeze (WB). Fig. 13
(a) IBEX-Lo He intensity map. (b) Model result for the ISN He intensity map. (c) Maximum fluxes in the He intensity maps for the IBEX-Lo observations and the model results. Solid curves are fit curves for the primary ISN He, and dashed curves are for the secondary He. (d) IBEX-Lo O intensity map. (e) Simulated ISN O intensity map. (f) Maximum fluxes of O intensity maps for the IBEX-Lo observations and the model results. Figures are adopted from Park et al. (2019)

The existence of secondary ISN O was proposed in the two-shock heliospheric model by Izmodenov et al. (1997). For the secondary ISN O, the most important resonant reaction is the charge exchange between interstellar O+ ion and ambient H atom (O++H→Osec+H+)\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$(O^{+} + H \rightarrow O_{\mathrm{sec}} + H^{+})$\end{document}. The sky maps of the IBEX-Lo O fluxes reveal a tail-like emission expanding toward lower longitude and higher latitude from the observational peak of the ISN O and Ne gas flow (Möbius et al. 2009; Park et al. 2015). The extended tail-like emission could be explained as the imprints of the secondary ISN O population. Baliukin et al. (2017) presented the results of modeling ISN O and Ne atoms through the heliospheric interface and inside the heliosphere based on a three-dimensional kinetic-MHD model of the SW interaction with the VLISM. They confirmed that the secondary ISN O population produces a similarly extended tail-like emission, which is seen in the IBEX-Lo O observations. Park et al. (2019) characterized the secondary ISN O flow at the HP with an analytical model for the directional distribution of the inflowing neutral atoms at Earth’s orbit. Figure 13 shows the ISN He and O flux maps from the IBEX-Lo observations and the results of the analytical model by Park et al. (2019). The emissions in the longitude of 150-210∘ result from the secondary ISN populations, which appear as the extended tail-like emission.

These HeII ions are resonantly scattered by the solar EUV radiation at λ0=\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
