The production of inner source PUIs is highly dependent on the composition, size, velocity, and density of the IDPs they interact with. The size distribution of the IDP population increases with smaller grain size due to the amount of dust-dust collisions (Ishimoto 2000). There is a large deficiency of IDPs of about 10−15\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$10^{-15}$\end{document} g to 10−12\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$10^{-12}$\end{document} g (i.e., beta-meteoroids) due to following hyperbolic orbits because of radiation pressure. However, grains smaller than beta-meteoroids (i.e., nanograins) have stable orbits close to the Sun (Mann et al. 2007).

Which production mechanism is dominant is still uncertain. Observations of inner source C+ and O+ show that C+/O+>1\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$C^{+}/O^{+}>1$\end{document} and decreases with SW speed (Taut et al. 2015). Simulations of neutralization, backscattering, and sputtering-induced recycling tend to reflect these observations (Quinn et al. 2019). However, observations of the radial profile, latitudinal profile, size distribution, composition, and morphology of IDPs close to the Sun are necessary to gain more insight.

The NH Solar Wind Around Pluto (SWAP) instrument (McComas et al. 2008a) observed interstellar H+ and He+ PUIs in the distant heliosphere, reporting observations at distances between ∼11.26\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$\sim 11.26$\end{document} and 38 au in the SW (McComas et al. 2017) and out to ∼47\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$\sim 47$\end{document} au McComas et al. (2021). Plasma observations well beyond the hydrogen ionization cavity show that the distant SW is mediated by PUIs. The observed PUI distributions, particularly H+ PUI, should have had sufficient time to evolve into a stable nearly-isotropic distribution. Observations of PUIs by the Ulysses Solar Wind Ion Composition Spectrometer (SWICS) instrument (Gloeckler et al. 1992) within the H ionization cavity, from about 1.4 to 5.4 au, identified numerous PUI species (H+, He+, N+, O+, Ne+) (e.g., Gloeckler and Geiss (1998)). The distributions tended to be highly anisotropic (Gloeckler et al. 1995), suggesting that the PUI scattering mfp was unusually long, although the precise reason for this is somewhat unclear. It is possible that the nature of the underlying turbulence responsible for the scattering of PUIs, being a superposition of a majority quasi-2D and a minority slab component, might be responsible for the long mfps.

The initial ring-beam PUI distribution is unstable to the excitation of Alfvénic modes (Lee and Ip 1987; Williams and Zank 1994; Zank 1999; Cannon et al. 2014b; Aggarwal et al. 2016; Fisher et al. 2016; Smith et al. 2017; Hollick et al. 2018a), and therefore modifies the underlying low-frequency turbulence field responsible for scattering PUIs. The excitation of Alfvénic fluctuations by PUIs is key to understanding the observed radial evolution of magnetic turbulence in the distant SW (Zank et al. 1996a; Matthaeus et al. 1999; Smith et al. 2001; Breech et al. 2008; Isenberg et al. 2010; Oughton et al. 2011; Zank et al. 2012; Adhikari et al. 2014, 2015; Wiengarten et al. 2016; Shiota et al. 2017; Zank et al. 2017; Adhikari et al. 2017). Furthermore the dissipation of low-frequency magnetic fluctuations heats the SW plasma and results in a non-adiabatic SW temperature profile and a slow temperature increase beyond ∼30\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$\sim 30$\end{document} au (Williams et al. 1995; Smith et al. 2001; Zank et al. 2017). PUI generation of low-frequency turbulence in the outer heliosphere also affects cosmic ray mfps (Zank et al. 1998; Florinski et al. 2003; Engelbrecht and Burger 2013; Chhiber et al. 2017; Engelbrecht 2017; Zhao et al. 2018).

The derivation of the equations for a PUI-mediated SW, including the structure of the TS, presented by Zank et al. (2014), Zank (2016), Zank et al. (2018) assumes that pre-existing and self-generated Alfvén waves scatter PUIs and a form of collisionless Chapman-Enskog expansion is then used to derive model equations describing the evolution of the PUI density ρp\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
