ISNs which cross the heliosphere and get ionized represent a suprathermal energy source moving through the SW along the mean-field at the SW speed. They resonantly excite sunward propagating, right-hand polarized waves which become left-hand polarized in the spacecraft frame (Lee and Ip 1987). As the waves propagate at the Alfvén speed and the ions are scattered in pitch angle, the waves are seen at spacecraft-frame frequencies fsc≥fi,c\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$f_{sc} \ge f_{i,c}$\end{document} where fi,c\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$f_{i,c}$\end{document} is the ion cyclotron frequency. While the process of scattering interstellar PUIs excites magnetic wave energy that drives the turbulence, it is not possible to observe that wave energy when it is absorbed by the turbulent cascade. When the turbulent cascade is sufficiently weak to allow the wave energy to accumulate to observable levels over many hours, the waves can be observed in the magnetic field data.

Waves due to newborn interstellar PUIs have been observed by magnetometers on numerous spacecraft including ACE (Argall et al. 2015; Fisher et al. 2016), Ulysses (Murphy et al. 1995; Cannon et al. 2013, 2014b,a; Aggarwal et al. 2016; Cannon et al. 2017; Argall et al. 2017), and Voyager (Joyce et al. 2010, 2012; Hollick et al. 2018a,b,c) and are reviewed by Smith et al. (2017). Figure 16 shows an example of Voyager 1 spectra exhibiting waves due to newborn interstellar H+\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}${\mathrm{H^{+}}}$\end{document} and He+ PUIs when the spacecraft was at 6.2 au. The waves due to H+ offer the stronger signal, but the ellipticity at fsc>fHe,c\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
