				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$\propto p^{-3}$\end{document}. Such a distribution, if left unmodified, contains an infinity amount of energy density and particle density. In reality, because particles suffer adiabatic energy loss and other possible loss mechanisms, the accelerated particles can never achieve this distribution over a wide range of particle momentum. As a result of acceleration, the pressure contained in accelerated particles can decrease the amplitude and wavenumber of compressible plasma waves, which in turn limits the momentum diffusion rate D0\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$D_{0}$\end{document}. Zhang (2010) and Zhang and Lee (2013) showed that the momentum diffusion and adiabatic cooling settle at some equilibrium rates so that the pressure of accelerated particles approaches a steady maximum value. At that point, a ∼p−5\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
