				\begin{document}$\sim p^{-5}$\end{document} power-law distribution function is established without details of wave or particle parameters.

With the condition that particles in particle acceleration regions can only produce a limit pressure in PUIs, Zhang and Schlickeiser (2012) established a maximum stochastic acceleration rate without an explosive increase of particle pressure. They showed under the maximum acceleration rate how particles could automatically establish a ∼p−5\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$~\sim p^{-5}$\end{document} distribution function in suprathermal energy tails. Figure 19 shows the calculation results of the omnidirectional PUI distribution function at 1 au, 5 au, and near the TS, compared with observations by ACE and Ulysses. Figure 20 shows radial dependence of PUI density and pressure calculated from the model and comparison to those expected radial variations of the SW. The slow down of the SW due to the mass loading of PUIs is neglected. As can be deduced from Fig. 20, the ratio of PUI to SW density and pressure increase with radial distances. By radial distances around 10 to 20 au, the pressure in PUIs dominates all magnetic field pressure, solar thermal pressure, and turbulence pressure all combined. It is only less than SW ram pressure. By the time it reaches the TS, the Mach number of the entire composite, which is equal to the square root of the ratio of SW ram pressure to PUI+SW internal pressure, is only around 3-4 at ∼80\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$\sim 80$\end{document} au even with unaccelerated PUI pressure (Fig. 21). As a result, the TS is no longer a supercritical shock. Particle acceleration of PUIs during their propagation through the interplanetary space partially contributes to PUI pressure buildup, thus further reducing the SW Mach number to below 2 in the quiet SW (Zone 1) at ∼80\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
